{"title_page": "Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television\n| former_name = Walt Disney Domestic Television Distribution{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}<br>Buena Vista Television\n| logo = File:Disney\u2013ABC_Home_Entertainment_and_Television_Distribution.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = Subsidiary\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1985|3}}\n| location_city = [[Burbank, California]]\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| area_served = [[North America]]\n| key_people = Janice Marinelli (President)\n| industry = [[Broadcast syndication|Television syndication]]\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer and International]]\n| homepage = {{URL|disneyabc.tv}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television''', also operating as '''ABC Syndication'''<ref name=\"snta\"/> (formerly known as '''Buena Vista Television, Inc.''', also known as '''Disney Domestic Television''' and currently known as '''Disney\u2013ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution'''), is the in-home sales and content distribution firm of the [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group]], a division of [[The Walt Disney Company]]. Content distribution responsibilities include domestic [[television]] [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]], domestic pay TV, Internet and cable video-on-demand (VOD), and pay-per-view outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/143/143802.html|title=Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television Company Profile|publisher=Yahoo Finance|accessdate=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nABC's first syndication arm, ABC Films (established in July 1953), was spun off as [[Worldvision Enterprises]] in March 1973 due to [[fin-syn]] laws (which have since been repealed).\n\nDespite having some TV shows and feature films, Disney only had two syndicated shows, ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club]]'' and ''[[The Mouse Factory]]'', prior to the formation of this unit.<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news|last1=Harmetz|first1=Aljean|title=Disney Creates TV syndication Unit |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/06/movies/disney-creates-tv-syndication-unit.html|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=The New York Times |date=March 6, 1985}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Buena Vista Television, Inc.===\n[[File:Buena Vista Television Logo.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Buena Vista Television logo used from 1997 to 2005.]]\nWalt Disney Pictures established a television syndication unit in 1985, with Robert Jacquemin as senior vice president of domestic television distribution. None of its animated feature films were planned to enter syndication at the time.<ref name=\"nyt1\"/> The division was incorporated as '''Buena Vista Television, Inc.''' on November 5, 1985.<ref name=ca>{{cite web|title=Buena Vista Television (C1356512)|url=https://businesssearch.sos.ca.gov/|website=Business Entity Detail|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref> with its first release in the first run syndication market with ''[[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|Siskel & Ebert]]''.<ref name=\"nyt0\"/> In 1990, the company offered its first game show, ''Challengers,'' into first-run syndication.<ref name=\"nyt0\">{{cite news|last1=Gerard|first1=Jeremy|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS: TELEVISION; Syndicators Find a Winner: The Successful Game Show|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/01/22/business/the-media-business-television-syndicators-find-a-winner-the-successful-game-show.html|accessdate=September 11, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=January 22, 1990}}</ref> The company produced the morning business show, ''Today's Business'', in August 1986, only to put an end to the show in April 1987, indicating that they were unable to get enough advertisers.<ref name=nyt2>{{cite news|last1=Adelson|first1=Rea|title=A Push for All-Business Radio |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/27/business/a-push-for-all-business-radio.html?pagewanted=all&mcubz=3|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=November 27, 1987}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1986, Buena Vista was shopping ''[[Duck Tales]]'' for a 1987 debut, with a 4\u20136 p.m. placement and a 2.5/3.5 syndicator/station ad split.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sobel|first1=Robert|title=Kids  syndication  marketplace  moving  at  frenzied pace|journal=Television/Radio Age|date=August 4, 1986 |volume=XXXIV|issue=1 |page=59 |url= http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-TV-Radio-Age/Issues/80s/1986/1986-08-04-RTVA.pdf |accessdate=September 13, 2017|publisher=Television Editorial Corp.|format=PDF}}</ref> In 1990, the company offered its first game show, ''[[The Challengers (game show)|Challengers]]'', for first run syndication.<ref name=\"nyt0\"/> In late 1990 and early 1991, after launching the [[Disney Afternoon]] syndicated block, Buena Vista had considered starting a new one-hour morning block to start in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal|title=INTV  DISPATCHES|journal=Broadcasting|date=January 7, 1991|page=14|url=http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1991/BC-1991-01-07.pdf|accessdate=September 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 1994, a reorganization of Disney took place in which [[Richard H. Frank]] became head of a newly formed Walt Disney Television and Telecommunications, which was split from [[The Walt Disney Studios (division)|The Walt Disney Studios]] and included Buena Vista TV.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weinraub|first=Bernard|title=Chairman of Disney Studios Resigns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/25/business/chairman-of-disney-studios-resigns.html|accessdate=April 28, 2014|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 25, 1994}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1996, due to ongoing post Disney\u2013[[Capital Cities Communications|Capital Cities/ABC]] merger realignment and retirement of its president, Walt Disney Television and Telecommunications's divisions were reassigned to other groups. Therefore, BVTV, as a part of Walt Disney Television International, was transferred to [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group|Capital Cities/ABC]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Roth, Iger Assume Expanded Responsibilities at the Walt Disney Company|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/ROTH%2c+IGER+ASSUME+EXPANDED+RESPONSIBILITIES+AT+THE+WALT+DISNEY+COMPANY-a018198127|accessdate=March 11, 2013|publisher=PR Newswire|date=April 16, 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, [[Starz Entertainment]] sued BVTV for breaching their agreement by allowing movies available online through [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iTunes Store]] and other outlets. The introduction of the [[Apple TV]] device forced Starz to file suit which hinged on the \"contractual definition of 'television'\" and whether complete TV exclusivity was granted, as Starz then had a secondary distribution deal with [[Netflix]].<ref name=mcn>{{cite web|last=Spangler|first=Todd|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-190612064.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042408/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-190612064.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=March 29, 2015|title=Coda. (a lawsuit between Starz Entertainment and Disney-ABC Domestic Television)|date=December 15, 2008|publisher=Multichannel News}}</ref>\n\n===Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television===\nIn May 2007, The Walt Disney Company announced plans to semi-retire the use of the [[Buena Vista (brand)|Buena Vista]] brand, instead focusing on the three core brands of [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], and [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fixmer|first=Fixmer|title=Disney to Drop Buena Vista Brand Name, People Say (Update1)|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=a0MG17nO.PG8&refer=home|accessdate=November 28, 2012|publisher=Bloomberg.com|date=April 25, 2007}}</ref> As a result, Buena Vista Television was rebranded as Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television (DADT).<ref name=mcn/> BVTV converted to a limited liability business form on April 10, 2009.<ref name=ca/><ref>{{cite web|title=Buena Vista Television LLC (200910010281)|url=http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/|website=Business Entity Detail|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy July 2008, DADT signed additional carriage agreements with [[Vudu]] and [[CinemaNow]] which was then added to the Starz lawsuit. On December 2, 2008, DADT and Starz Entertainment settled their online distribution lawsuit with the terms undisclosed.<ref name=mcn/>\n\n==First-run programming==\n===Current===\n*''[[Live with Kelly and Ryan]]''<ref name=snta>{{cite web|url=http://www.snta.com/php/display.php?p=PR_SP_syndicator&s_id=4|title=ABC Syndication Members Profiles|publisher=Syndicated Network Television Association|accessdate=July 2, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203064953/http://www.snta.com/php/display.php?p=PR_SP_syndicator&s_id=4|archivedate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> (1988\u2013present; produced by [[WABC-TV]])\n*''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (U.S. game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire]]'' (2002\u2013present; w/ [[Valleycrest Productions]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Just|first1=Olivia|title=Disney moves filming of 'Millionaire' to Stamford|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Disney-moves-filming-of-Millionaire-to-Stamford-5597151.php|accessdate=May 22, 2015|work=CT Post|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation|Hearst Media Services Connecticut, LLC]]|date=July 3, 2014}}</ref> [[Times Square Studios (division)|Times Square Studios]],<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last=Stelter|first=Brian|title=Head of ABC\u2019s Daytime Programming Is Leaving|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/02/head-of-abcs-daytime-programming-is-leaving/|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 2, 2011}}</ref> [[2waytraffic]])\n*''[[Right This Minute]]'' (2016\u2013present; w/ MagicDust Television, [[Cox Media Group]], [[Gray Television]] and [[E. W. Scripps Company]])<ref>[https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/fablife-cancelled-tyra-banks-chrissy-teigen-talk-show-1201683544/ ''FABLife'' Officially Canceled Following Tyra Banks\u2019 Departure, Disney/ABC Picks Up ''Right This Minute''] at Variety.com</ref><ref>[http://deadline.com/2016/01/rightthisminute-disney-abc-stations-1201686477/ Disney/ABC Takes Over Distribution Of ''RightThisMinute'', Clears It On ABC Stations] at Deadline.com</ref>\n*''[[America's Funniest Home Videos]]'' (1989\u2013present; w/ [[Vin Di Bona Productions]])\n*''[[Litton's Weekend Adventure]]'' (2011\u2013present; E/I programming block from Litton Entertainment; exclusively for ABC affiliates)\n*''[[Pickler & Ben]]'' (2017\u2013present; w/ [[E. W. Scripps Company]])\n\n===Former===\n*''[[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|At the Movies]]'' (originally ''Siskel & Ebert''<ref name=\"nyt0\"/>/''At the Movies with Ebert and Roeper'') (1986\u20132010)\n*''[[Bill Nye the Science Guy]]'' (1993\u20131998; w/[[KCTS]] of Seattle and [[Rabbit Ears Productions]])\n*''[[Debt (game show)|Debt]]'' (1996\u20131998; w/ Faded Denim Productions and [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]])\n*''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'' (1994\u20131998; w/ The Black/Marlens Company and [[Touchstone Television]])\n*''[[FABLife]]'' (2015\u20132016; w/ Summerdale Productions)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Villarreal|first1=Yvonne|title=ABC stations pick up Tyra Banks-led daytime talk show for 2015|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-ct-abc-stations-picks-up-tyra-banksled-daytime-talk-show-for-2015-20141020-story.html|accessdate=December 11, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>\n*''[[Legend of the Seeker]]'' (2008\u20132010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117989925.html |title=Sam Raimi banks on Disney's 'Seeker'|accessdate=2008-11-07|last=Thielman|first=Sam|date=August 1, 2008|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n*''[[Katie (talk show)|Katie]]'' (2012\u20132014)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/20/business/media/katie-to-end-production-in-june-after-two-seasons.html|title=''Katie'' to End Production in June After Two Seasons|last=Carter|first=Bill|work=The New York Times|date=December 19, 2013|accessdate=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n*''[[On the Red Carpet]]'' (2013\u20132014)<ref>{{cite web|last=Albiniak|first=Paige|title=Disney-ABC Goes Wall-to-Wall With 'On the Red Carpet'|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/news-articles/disney-abc-goes-wall-wall-red-carpet/114409|accessdate=December 3, 2014|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=April 29, 2013}}</ref>\n*''[[Teen Win, Lose or Draw]]'' (1989\u20131992; w/Burt & Bert Productions, Kline & Friends and Stone Stanley Entertainment)\n*''[[The Challengers (game show)|The Challengers]]'' (1990\u201391; w/[[Dick Clark Productions]]<ref name=nyt0/> and Ron Greenberg Productions)\n*''[[The Disney Afternoon]]''<ref name=nyt0/> (1990\u20131997)\n** ''[[Duck Tales]]'' (1987\u20131990)<ref name=Syndicated>{{cite news|author=Wayne Friedman|title=SYNDICATED TV: HARDBALL WITH THE BIG GUYS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/04/15/business/syndicated-tv-hardball-with-the-big-guys.html|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 15, 1990}}</ref>\n** ''[[Chip 'n Dale: Rescue Rangers]]'' (1989\u20131990)<ref name=\"Syndicated\" />\n**''[[TaleSpin]]'' (1990\u201391<ref name=bc>{{cite journal|title=MORE NEW CHILDREN'S PLAYERS FOR DISNEY|journal=Broadcasting|url=http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1991/BC-1991-01-07.pdf|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref>)\n**''[[Darkwing Duck]]'' (1991\u20131992) <ref name=bc/>\n**''[[Goof Troop]]'' (1992) <ref name=bc/>\n**''[[Bonkers (TV series)|Bonkers]]'' (1993\u20131994) <ref name=bc/>\n*''[[The Wayne Brady Show]]'' (2001\u20132004)<ref name=lat>{{cite web|title=Low ratings spell end of Brady show|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/jan/13/entertainment/et-quick13.2|accessdate=December 11, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=AP|date=January 13, 2004}}</ref>\n*''Today's Business'' (August 1986 \u2013 April 1987) morning business show which cost $500,000 a month to make<ref name=nyt1/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb company|0078478|Disney-ABC Domestic Television}}\n*{{URL|http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/143/143802.html|Disney-ABC Domestic Television}} Company Profile at Yahoo Finance\n\n{{Disney}}\n{{DAFT}}\n{{ABC Kids}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Disney-ABC Domestic Television}}\n[[Category:Disney Media Networks]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Television syndication distributors]]\n[[Category:Disney production studios]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Buena Vista Television LLC\n| trade_name = Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television<br>Disney\u2013ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution\n| former_name = Walt Disney Domestic Television Distribution{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}<br>Buena Vista Television (1985\u20132007)\n| logo = Disney\u2013ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution.svg\n| type = Subsidiary\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1985|3}}\n| location_city = [[Burbank, California]]\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| area_served = [[North America]]\n| key_people = \n| industry = [[Broadcast syndication|Television syndication]]\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]]<br>([[The Walt Disney Company]])\n| homepage = {{URL|disneyabc.tv}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Buena Vista Television LLC''' (operating under the names '''Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television''' and '''Disney\u2013ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution''' and also operating as '''ABC Syndication''';<ref name=\"snta\"/> formerly known as '''Buena Vista Television, Inc.''' and '''Disney Domestic Television''') is the in-home sales and content distribution firm of [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]], a division of [[The Walt Disney Company]]. Content distribution responsibilities include domestic [[television]] [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]], domestic pay TV, Internet and cable video-on-demand (VOD), and pay-per-view outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/143/143802.html|title=Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television Company Profile|publisher=Yahoo Finance|accessdate=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nABC's first syndication arm, ABC Films (established in July 1953), was spun off as [[Worldvision Enterprises]] in March 1973 due to [[fin-syn]] laws (which have since been repealed).\n\nDespite having some TV shows and feature films, Disney only had two syndicated shows, ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club]]'' and ''[[The Mouse Factory]]'', prior to the formation of this unit.<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news|last1=Harmetz|first1=Aljean|title=Disney Creates TV syndication Unit |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/06/movies/disney-creates-tv-syndication-unit.html|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=The New York Times |date=March 6, 1985}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Buena Vista Television, Inc.===\n[[File:Buena Vista Television Logo.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Buena Vista Television logo used from 1997 to 2005.]]\nDisney established a television syndication unit in 1985, with Robert Jacquemin as senior vice president of domestic television distribution. None of its animated feature films were planned to enter syndication at the time.<ref name=\"nyt1\"/> The division was incorporated as '''Buena Vista Television, Inc.''' on November 5, 1985,<ref name=ca>{{cite web|title=Buena Vista Television (C1356512)|url=https://businesssearch.sos.ca.gov/|website=Business Entity Detail|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref> with its first release in the first-run syndication market called ''[[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|Siskel & Ebert]]''.<ref name=\"nyt0\"/>  The company produced the business-oriented morning show, ''Today's Business'', in August 1986, only to put an end to the show in April 1987, indicating that they were unable to get enough advertisers.<ref name=nyt2>{{cite news|last1=Adelson|first1=Rea|title=A Push for All-Business Radio |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/27/business/a-push-for-all-business-radio.html?pagewanted=all&mcubz=3|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=November 27, 1987}}</ref> In 1990, the company offered its first game show, ''Challengers'', into first-run syndication.<ref name=\"nyt0\">{{cite news|last1=Gerard|first1=Jeremy|title=The Media Business: Television; Syndicators Find a Winner: The Successful Game Show|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/01/22/business/the-media-business-television-syndicators-find-a-winner-the-successful-game-show.html|accessdate=September 11, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=January 22, 1990}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1986, Buena Vista was shopping ''[[DuckTales]]'' for a 1987 debut, with a 4\u20136 p.m. placement and a 2.5/3.5 syndicator/station ad split.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Sobel|first1=Robert|title=Kids  syndication  marketplace  moving  at  frenzied pace|magazine=Television/Radio Age|date=August 4, 1986|volume=XXXIV|issue=1|page=59|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-TV-Radio-Age/Issues/80s/1986/1986-08-04-RTVA.pdf|accessdate=September 13, 2017|format=PDF|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20141127203506/http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-TV-Radio-Age/Issues/80s/1986/1986-08-04-RTVA.pdf|archive-date=November 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In late 1990 and early 1991, after launching the [[Disney Afternoon]] syndicated block, Buena Vista had considered starting a new one-hour morning block to start in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal|title=INTV  DISPATCHES|journal=Broadcasting|date=January 7, 1991|page=14|url=http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1991/BC-1991-01-07.pdf|accessdate=September 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 1994, a reorganization of Disney took place in which [[Richard H. Frank]] became head of a newly formed Walt Disney Television and Telecommunications, which was split from [[The Walt Disney Studios (division)|The Walt Disney Studios]] and included Buena Vista TV.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weinraub|first=Bernard|title=Chairman of Disney Studios Resigns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/25/business/chairman-of-disney-studios-resigns.html|accessdate=April 28, 2014|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 25, 1994}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1996, due to the ongoing post Disney\u2013[[Capital Cities Communications|Capital Cities/ABC]] merger realignment and the retirement of its president, Walt Disney Television and Telecommunications' divisions were reassigned to other groups. Therefore, Buena Vista TV, as a part of Walt Disney Television International, was transferred to [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group|Capital Cities/ABC]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Roth, Iger Assume Expanded Responsibilities at the Walt Disney Company|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/ROTH%2c+IGER+ASSUME+EXPANDED+RESPONSIBILITIES+AT+THE+WALT+DISNEY+COMPANY-a018198127|accessdate=March 11, 2013|publisher=PR Newswire|date=April 16, 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, [[Starz Entertainment]] sued Buena Vista TV for breaching their agreement by allowing films to be available online through [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iTunes Store]] and other outlets. The introduction of the [[Apple TV]] device forced Starz to file suit, which hinged on the \"contractual definition of 'television'\" and whether complete TV exclusivity was granted, as Starz then had a secondary distribution deal with [[Netflix]].<ref name=mcn>{{cite web|last=Spangler|first=Todd|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-190612064.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042408/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-190612064.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 29, 2015|title=Coda. (a lawsuit between Starz Entertainment and Disney-ABC Domestic Television)|date=December 15, 2008|publisher=Multichannel News}}</ref>\n\n===Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television===\nIn May 2007, The Walt Disney Company announced plans to semi-retire the use of the [[Buena Vista (brand)|Buena Vista]] brand in favor of focusing on the three core brands of [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], and [[ESPN]] instead.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fixmer|first=Andy|title=Disney to Drop Buena Vista Brand Name, People Say (Update1)|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=a0MG17nO.PG8&refer=home|accessdate=November 28, 2012|publisher=Bloomberg.com|date=April 25, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918060836/https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=a0MG17nO.PG8&refer=home|archive-date=18 September 2011}}</ref> As a result, Buena Vista Television was rebranded as Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television (DADT).<ref name=mcn/> Buena Vista TV converted to a limited liability business form on April 10, 2009.<ref name=ca/><ref>{{cite web|title=Buena Vista Television LLC (200910010281)|url=https://businesssearch.sos.ca.gov/Document/RetrievePDF?Id=200910010281-831852|website=Business Entity Detail|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy July 2008, Disney\u2013ABC Domestic TV signed additional carriage agreements with [[Vudu]] and [[CinemaNow]], which was then added to the Starz lawsuit. On December 2, 2008, Disney\u2013ABC Domestic TV and Starz Entertainment settled their online distribution lawsuit with the terms undisclosed.<ref name=mcn/>\n\nDistribution units were transfer to Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer and International (DTCI) as part of [[The Walt Disney Company]]\u2019s March 14, 2018 strategic reorganization [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|in anticipation of integrating]] [[21st Century Fox]]'s assets.<ref name=dl>{{cite news|last1=Chmielewski|first1=Dawn C.|title=Disney Announces Reorganization, Names Kevin Mayer Head Of New Direct-To-Consumer Unit, Adds Consumer Products To Bob Chapek\u2019s Portfolio|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/disney-reorganization-kevin-mayer-direct-to-consumer-bob-chapeks-consumer-products-1202337810/|accessdate=March 16, 2018|work=Deadline|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In February 2020, Disney licensed 21 TV series, from ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' to ''[[Witches of East End (TV series)|Witches of East End]]'' including ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'' and ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', to Amazon-owned [[IMDb#IMDb TV|IMDb TV]] ad supported streaming service.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Spangler |first1=Todd  |title=Amazon\u2019s IMDb TV Inks Disney Pact for Free Streaming of \u2018Lost,\u2019 \u2018Desperate Housewives,\u2019 More |url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/imdb-tv-free-streaming-lost-desperate-housewives-1203494179/ |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=Variety |date=February 5, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==First-run programming==\n===Current===\n* ''[[Live with Kelly and Ryan]]''<ref name=snta>{{cite web|url=http://www.snta.com/php/display.php?p=PR_SP_syndicator&s_id=4|title=ABC Syndication Members Profiles|publisher=Syndicated Network Television Association|accessdate=July 2, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203064953/http://www.snta.com/php/display.php?p=PR_SP_syndicator&s_id=4|archivedate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> (1988\u2013present) produced by [[WABC-TV]]\n* ''[[Right This Minute]]'' (2016\u2013present) produced by MagicDust Television, [[Cox Media Group]], [[Gray Television]] and [[E. W. Scripps Company]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wagmeister |first1=Elizabeth |title=\u2018FABLife\u2019 Officially Canceled Following Tyra Banks\u2019 Departure, Disney/ABC Picks Up \u2018Right This Minute\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/fablife-cancelled-tyra-banks-chrissy-teigen-talk-show-1201683544/ |accessdate=August 7, 2019 |work=Variety |date=January 20, 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n* ''[[Tamron Hall (talk show)|Tamron Hall]]'' (2019\u2013present) produced by Summerdale Productions and May Avenue Productions<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petski |first1=Denise  |title=\u2018Tamron Hall\u2019 Syndicated Daytime Talk Show Gets Fall Premiere Date |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/tamron-hall-syndicated-daytime-talk-show-fall-premiere-date-1202568869/ |accessdate=March 4, 2019 |work=Deadline |date=March 4, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* ''[[Litton's Weekend Adventure]]'' (2011\u2013present) E/I programming block from Litton Entertainment; exclusively for ABC affiliates\n\n===Former===\n* ''[[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|At the Movies]]'' (1986\u20132010), originally ''Siskel & Ebert & the Movies''<ref name=\"nyt0\"/>/''At the Movies with Ebert and Roeper'' \n* ''[[Bill Nye the Science Guy]]'' (1993\u20131998), with [[KCTS]] of Seattle and [[Rabbit Ears Productions]]\n* ''[[Debt (game show)|Debt]]'' (1996\u20131998), with Faded Denim Productions and [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]]\n* ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'' (1994\u20131998), with The Black/Marlens Company and [[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]]\n* ''[[FABLife]]'' (2015\u20132016), with Summerdale Productions and The Tyra Banks Company<ref>{{cite news|last1=Villarreal|first1=Yvonne|title=ABC stations pick up Tyra Banks-led daytime talk show for 2015|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-ct-abc-stations-picks-up-tyra-banksled-daytime-talk-show-for-2015-20141020-story.html|accessdate=December 11, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 20, 2014}}</ref>\n* ''[[Legend of the Seeker]]'' (2008\u20132010)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117989925.html |title=Sam Raimi banks on Disney's 'Seeker'|accessdate=2008-11-07|last=Thielman|first=Sam|date=August 1, 2008|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n* ''Iyanla'' (2001\u2013200